// DISABLED. The runner will skip this file because it has no recognized header
// (`// expected_exit:` / `// expects_build_fail:`) — see scripts/test-rust-interop or
// TesterRust's rust_interop module for the parse logic.
//
// Why disabled: Vec::push takes &mut self. With the Backend fix that distinguishes Rust
// `&T` from `&mut T` in the emitted C param qualifier, the build succeeds and the FFI
// call is made cleanly at runtime (no crash, no link error). HOWEVER — Vale stores
// `extern struct Vec<T> imm` as a 24-byte by-value struct on the stack. When the user
// writes `v.push(1)`, Vale copies `v` into a temporary, hands a pointer to that temporary
// to push, push mutates the temporary, and then the temporary is discarded. The original
// `v` is untouched, so subsequent `v.len()` reads back 0 instead of 3.
//
// This is a Vale-language-level limitation, not an FFI bug: there is no surface syntax
// for `&mut`-style extern receivers that would give the user-side binding a stable
// address with propagating mutations. Until that surface exists (or an equivalent
// ValeRuster-side wrapper does the dance), calling Rust mutator methods from Vale
// silently loses the mutation — which is unacceptable to ship.
//
// Test re-enabled when the semantic story for mutators lands. Original program below.
//
//   import rust.std.vec.Vec;
//
//   exported func main() int {
//     v = Vec<int>.with_capacity(8i64);
//     v.push(1);
//     v.push(2);
//     v.push(3);
//     return v.len().TruncateI64ToI32();
//   }
